description: Performed in my duties as a CI/HUMINT Intelligence Analyst supporting AFOSI in the Counter Threat & Counter Intelligence mission of keeping Air Force personnel and assets protected on Bagram Airfield. Duties include data mining, conducting reports officer duties for HUMINT-based intelligence reports, providing in-depth intelligence analysis on HUMINT reporting, and coordinating liaison duties with external action units to target Afghan terrorist/insurgent/militia members for U.S. or Host Nation custody based on intelligence reporting. Duties include, but are not limited to, the production of intelligence threat briefs to AFOSI EDET 2405 elements that conduct missions outside of the wire. Mission briefs include the incorporation of HUMINT threat reporting, Significant Activities, Atmospherics, or presence of Targets/insurgent groups in the mission area/route. Analyst is responsible for dissecting intelligence reporting and de-conflicting biographical information that may/may not pertain to AFOSI EDET 2405’s HUMINT Targets/Persons of Interest. Analyst incorporates the use of CIDNE, TIGR, M3-AMHS, HOT-R, and other miscellaneous programs/databases on a daily basis. Analyst is also responsible for supporting AFOSI EDET 2405’s response to criminal investigations involving US Air Force personnel, equipment, or military installations in the Afghanistan Theater of Operations (ATO).

description: Worked as a Human Intelligence Analyst supporting intelligence operations in the Detention Facility in Parwan (DFIP). Analyst is responsible for reviewing, comparing, and analyzing Human Intelligence (HUMINT), Signals Intelligence (SIGINT), Imagery Intelligence (IMINT), and other forms of intelligence that create a common picture as to why insurgent detainees are currently in U.S. custody. Analyst is responsible for liaison work with adjacent and subordinate Battle Space Owners (BSOs) and Capturing Units to ensure a seamless transfer of information that directly pertains to the Detainee for his presentation to the Detainee Review Board (DRB). Analyst is responsible for being a neutral party in the review of information assessed to be about the Detainee and to highlight inconsistencies in HUMINT reporting, SIGINT, and Coalition Forces Sworn Statements that may or may not be about the Detainee. Analyst works daily with military lawyers (referred to as Recorders) and military Personal Representatives to present an accurate, detailed account of the Detainee and his alleged activities within the Afghan insurgency. The accurate presentation of intelligence information on the Detainee will often highlight the Detainee’s guilt or innocence based on existing evidence. Analyst participates in analytic exchanges with joint, allied, and coalition intelligence organizations while maintaining situational awareness of political, economic, diplomatic, criminal, military, paramilitary and terrorism-related developments. Analyst coordinates with military and civilian personnel of higher echelon intelligence agencies and organizations to expand information collection on the known persons of interest. Analyst reviews collection products to ensure the collection focus is being met and serves as principal advisor to the client, evaluation, analysis, production, and dissemination of human intelligence information.

description: Worked as an Intelligence Analyst in Baghdad, Iraq for the JIOC Kurd Team. Responsibilities included collecting, analyzing, and compiling intelligence data to brief the Commanding General, the USF-I J2, or other senior military and civilian officials within the CENTCOM Theater of Operations. Analyst was responsible for data mining and creating intelligence products based on raw intelligence. Products included, but were not limited to, leadership biographies, Daily Intelligence Summaries (DISUMs), Intelligence Updates, Information Papers (IPs), Battle Update Assessment (BUA) contributions, Human Intelligence (HUMINT) and Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) Evaluations, Running Estimates, and Requests for Information (RFI). Once intelligence products were researched, created, and disseminated to the widest customer base possible, analyst followed up with an evaluation based on HUMINT, SIGINT, and CIA reporting used within the products created. Assigned to the Kurdistan Regional Government (KRG) political section within the Kurd Team. Responsible for knowing the leadership of the major Kurdish political parties within Iraqi Kurdistan and how they are affected by each other, the Government of Iraq, Turkey, Iran, and the Arab population within Iraqi Kurdistan. Analyst had overall working knowledge of the PMESII construct within the Iraqi Kurdistan area of concentration.

description: Served as a Senior Instructor/Course Developer for the Distributed Common Ground System – Army (DCGS-A) in the New Systems Training and Integration Offices (NSTIO). Duties and responsibilities are to train units stateside and units that are deploying to OEF and OIF theaters of operation, on the DCGS-A Automated Intelligence System. These responsibilities include training students in a classroom environment, as well as traveling to their stateside duty stations in the Mobile Training Team. Duties also include reviewing, writing, and/or rewriting DCGS-A courseware to match the training standards maintained by the United States Army Intelligence Command (USAIC). Mobile Training Team travel includes: twice to Fort Bragg, NC, once to Fort Indiantown Gap, PA, once to Camp Bullis, TX and approximately five training events in Fort Huachuca. Trained U.S. Army active, U.S. Army Reserve, and U.S. Navy units on the DCGS-A automated system for further use in the Afghanistan (OEF) and Iraq (OIF) theater of operations. Tasks include training students on Middle Eastern Culture and Terrorism, Doctrine Tactics and Training, Asymmetric Warfare, and the Capabilities of DCGS-A. These tasks are taught to students so that they understand their role as war fighters while using DCGS-A. Programs used in DCGS-A include Messaging, Multi-Function Work Station, Psi Jabber, MFWS Collaboration Tool, Messaging, Query Tree NG, Pathfinder Client and Pathfinder Web, Map View, ArcGIS, MFWS Alert Manager, Ticker Tape, Named Area of Interest (NAI) Tool, and Analysis and Exploration of Information Sources (AXIS). Students are taught how to use these tools so that they can receive, analyze, process, and disseminate intelligence data in Near Real Time (NRT) fashion. Students are taught how to use mapping tools such as ArcGIS and Map View to visual create entities on a military map and brief their commanders.

description: Performed 35F Intelligence Analyst Instructor functions with USAIC&FH/GDIT Corporation. In this position, it was my responsibility to train Initial Entry soldiers in a classroom environment on how to become a 35F All-Source Intelligence Analyst. Training was focused on soldier comprehension of all 96B tasks to include instructions on how to conduct briefings in military format, draw military overlays, understand military symbology, comprehension of the Intelligence Preparation of the Battlefield (IPB), incorporating the Intelligence Decision Making Process in the planning of military operations, Middle Eastern Cultural Awareness Training, knowledge of Boolean Logic data search strings, the Arabic naming convention, & culminating Field Training Exercise prior to student graduation from the school house. Students were focused on the areas of enemy Tactics, Techniques, & Procedures (TTPs) and were given real world examples of personalities, activities, & locations to base their analysis off of. Middle Eastern Cultural Awareness & Counter-Terrorism analysis was implemented in the analytical processes of student Practical Exercises. Students were taught specifically how to analyze enemy intentions while focusing on Asymmetric Warfare tactics. Students were also trained on the ability to categorize human information sources & intentions, local national sentiment towards U.S. & Coalition Forces, as well as learning the motivations to enemy activities. Students focused on terrorist groups, insurgent groups, religious activities & motivations, & civil activities. Comprehension & knowledge of specific tasks were evaluated based off of instructor monitored written student exams. Trained soldiers how to operate automated programs such as FalconView, ASAS-Lite, Analyst Notebook, Pathfinder Web, & ArcGis, as well as other user tools in a garrison and/or deployed environment. Position also included writing, reviewing, & testing courseware that was written in the 35F school house.
